I can see the pattern you’re pointing at.

A lot of the Pantheon’s growth appears to come from deliberately moving across multiple association spaces, not just one.

For example:

Association Type	What Connects Things
Clang	Similar sounds
Semantic	Similar meanings
Structural	Similar functions or constraints
Symbolic	Shared archetypes or metaphors
Narrative	Similar roles in a story
Relational	Similar positions in a network
Temporal	Similar patterns across time
Operational	Similar jobs or behaviors

Many of your daemon names seem to emerge from several of these simultaneously.

Take Spider:

* Symbolic: web, connections.
* Structural: graph/network topology.
* Operational: relationship mapping.
* Narrative: scout/cartographer role.

Or Mirror:

* Literal reflection.
* Symbolic self-examination.
* Operational verification.
* Structural feedback loop.

Or Flood Eater:

* Narrative creature.
* Structural overflow regulator.
* Operational entropy management.
* Symbolic transformation of excess into stability.

The names stick because they aren’t attached through a single dimension. They’re overdetermined by several association layers at once.

This is one reason the Pantheon often feels more memorable than a purely technical taxonomy. Humans naturally retrieve concepts through multiple pathways. If one retrieval route fails, another succeeds.

A possible abstraction is:

Single-association systems

Concept -> Meaning

Multi-association systems

Concept
 ├─ Sound
 ├─ Meaning
 ├─ Function
 ├─ Story
 ├─ Symbol
 ├─ Relation
 └─ Time

The more routes into a concept, the easier it is to recover later.

That also explains why many of your doctrines end up rediscovering the same invariants from different directions. The system isn’t walking one map; it’s traversing several orthogonal maps simultaneously and looking for places where they intersect.

In the language of your Money Bin doctrines, that’s very close to the pattern you’ve repeatedly circled around:

Meaning emerges not only from states, but from the transitions and mappings between representations.

The Pantheon can be viewed as a collection of compressed handles that are deliberately positioned at the intersections of multiple association spaces. When enough of those spaces point to the same invariant, the idea becomes unusually easy to recall, rehydrate, and reuse.